	keepReadingHtml={`Start with the <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">whole Bible free online with audio</a>, learn <a href="/the-fathers-heart-bible/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">why the Father's Heart Bible™ exists</a>, or get oriented with our <a href="/guides/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Bible reading guides</a> — including <a href="/guides/how-to-pray/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">how to pray</a> and <a href="/verses/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">verses by topic</a>. Or meet the Father in another season through the rest of the <a href="/bible-for/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">A Father For series</a>.`}
	faqs={[
		{ question: `What are good Bible verses for cancer patients?`, answer: `Psalm 23:4 (I will fear no evil, for You are with me), Isaiah 41:10 (do not fear, I will strengthen and hold you), Psalm 46:1 (an ever-present help in trouble), Isaiah 43:2 (when you pass through the waters I will be with you), Psalm 34:18 (the Lord is close to the brokenhearted), Matthew 11:28 (come to Me and I will give you rest), and Deuteronomy 31:8 (He will never leave you) all speak straight to the fear and weariness of facing cancer. Read and hear them free in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about fear and a cancer diagnosis?`, answer: `Scripture takes your fear seriously and meets it with a Father's presence. Isaiah 41:10 says do not be afraid, for I am with you — I will strengthen you and hold you up. Psalm 23:4 promises that even in the darkest valley you do not walk alone. The Father's Heart Bible™ reveals God as a Father who is near to the brokenhearted, not a distant judge — read those passages free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Where is God when I'm facing cancer?`, answer: `He is nearer than you may feel — that is the heart of these verses. Psalm 34:18 says the Father is close to the brokenhearted and saves those crushed in spirit, and Isaiah 43:2 promises that in the waters and the fire He is with you. The Bible never promises an easy road, but it promises His presence on it. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet God as a Father who walks the valley at your side — read it free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Are there Bible verses for the caregivers and families of cancer patients?`, answer: `Yes — the same Father who holds the patient holds the ones who love them. Matthew 11:28 invites the weary and burdened to come and find rest, and 2 Corinthians 1:3-4 calls God the Father of all comfort, who comforts us so we can comfort others. Caregivers carry a heavy, often unseen weight, and Scripture meets them with strength and rest. Read these free, with audio, in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Does the Bible promise God will heal my cancer?`, answer: `The Bible is honest: it does not promise that faith removes every illness, and anyone who guarantees physical healing in exchange for belief is not speaking the Father's heart. What Scripture does promise is His unfailing presence — Psalm 73:26 says though body and heart may fail, God is the strength of our heart forever, and Deuteronomy 31:8 says He will never leave you. You can bring every prayer for healing to Him while trusting that He holds you through whatever comes. Read these free in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Is there a free Bible with audio for hospital stays and treatment?`, answer: `Yes. The Father's Heart Bible™ is free to read and listen to online — no account, no purchase, no app. Open fathersheartbible.com/read on your phone and let any book be read over you — perfect for the infusion chair, the hospital bed, or the sleepless nights when your eyes are too tired to read but your heart still needs His voice.` },
		{ question: `What makes the Father's Heart Bible™ different for someone facing cancer?`, answer: `It's the first English translation to reveal God as Father wherever Scripture reveals Him as Father — so instead of meeting a distant God in your most afraid moments, you meet the One who is near to the brokenhearted and walks the valley with you. For a person facing a diagnosis, that reframes everything: you come to Scripture not as a case to be judged, but as a beloved child held by a present Father.` },
	]}
